33","1148–1200":"1148–1200","1152–Female":"1152–Deceased","Abt 1204":"about 1204","1241":"1241","1175":"1175","1174":"1174","1152":"1152","1284":"1284","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Abt 1207":"about 1207","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","Abt 1233":"about 1233","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1233":"1233","about 1205":"about 1205","1207":"1207","Redbourn, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Of Drayton, Oxon, Engl.":"Drayton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Radbourn, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England","Of Redburn":"Melbourne, Victoria, Australia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Arden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: possibly a habitational name from a localityin Northumberland called Darden."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":41,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Arch